  description="How to pay in Korea as a visitor: cards vs cash, the T-money transit card, prepaid travel cards, ATMs, and where you'll still need won in hand."
>
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Essentials</p>
      <h1>Money & Payments in Korea</h1>
      <p>Cards work almost everywhere — but carry some cash too.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <article class="article wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Quick answer</h2>
      <p>
        Korea is highly card-friendly — most restaurants, shops, and cafés take
        international cards. Carry some cash (Korean won) for traditional-market
        food stalls and small vendors, and get a T-money card for transit.
      </p>

      <h2>Cards vs cash</h2>
      <p>
        Contactless and chip cards are accepted almost everywhere, including many
        taxis. The main exceptions are <strong>traditional markets</strong> and
        small independent food stalls, where cash is often preferred — so keep a
        few small bills on you when you go to eat at markets.
      </p>

      <h2>Prepaid travel & transit cards</h2>
      <p>
        A <strong>T-money card</strong> covers subways, buses, and many taxis and
        can also pay at convenience stores. Prepaid travel cards aimed at
        visitors bundle transit with card payments and are sold at the airport
        and convenience stores — convenient if you'd rather not carry much cash.
      </p>

      <h2>ATMs & currency</h2>
      <p>
        Look for ATMs marked "Global" or "Foreign Card" (common in convenience
        stores and airports) to withdraw won with an overseas card. Exchanging
        some cash before or on arrival is handy for your first day.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="disclosure">
      General guidance only; card acceptance, fees, and card products change.
      Check with your bank and official sources before relying on specifics.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
